109. Am J Trop Med Hyg. 1998 Aug;59(2):341-6. doi: 10.4269/ajtmh.1998.59.341.

Reduction of Culiseta melanura fitness by eastern equine encephalomyelitis 
virus.

Scott TW(1), Lorenz LH.

Author information:
(1)Department of Entomology, University of Maryland, College Park 20472, USA.

The traditional view of interactions between arboviruses and their arthropod 
vectors is that vector hosts become increasingly resistant to parasites; 
parasite attenuation occurs; or through the process of coevolution, resistance 
and attenuation occur in concert. Detrimental effects from arboviruses are only 
seen when vector and virus are not yet well adapted. Results from this study 
indicate that eastern equine encephalomyelitis (EEE) virus reduces survival and 
reproduction (fitness) of the mosquito Culiseta melanura, which is required for 
transmission of EEE virus in North America. Mosquito virulence was not 
measurably attenuated in virus isolates recovered 55 year apart. This virus did 
not affect the ability of mosquitoes to obtain a blood meal or the rate of 
mosquito oocyte development. Results from this study support those from earlier 
investigations with other mosquito-virus interactions and suggest that 
reproductively successful arboviruses can have detrimental effects on their 
mosquito vectors.

